<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Research Councils UK (WSC023)</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Research Councils UK (WSC023)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Research Councils UK (RCUK)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is the strategic partnership of the UK's seven Research Councils. We invest annually around £3 billion in research. Our focus is on excellence with impact. We nurture the highest quality research, as judged by international peer review providing the UK wi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">th a competitive advantage. Global research requires we sustain a diversity of funding approaches, fostering international collaborations, and providing access to the best facilities and infrastructure, and locating skilled researchers in stimulating envir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">onments. Our research achieves impact – the demonstrable contribution to society and the economy made by knowledge and skilled people. To deliver impact, researchers and businesses need to engage and collaborate with the public, business, government and ch</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aritable organisations.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Our Vision for Research Careers and Diversity:</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research Councils UK (RCUK) believe that investment in attracting, training</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and managing the next generation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of world-class researchers makes a major</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">contribution to the impact of research and benefits the economic and social</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wellbeing of the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We will use our position and influence to lead cultural change in the HE sector,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in particular through our support for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the Vitae® Programme</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the Concordat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to Support the Career Development of Researchers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and the development of our recently published statement of expectations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(see below) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">which describes how we expect those in receipt of our funding to promote and lead</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> cultural change in relation to equality and diversity.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Our vision is:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to ensure that the best potential researchers from a diverse </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">population</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> attracted into research careers</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to enhance the quality of research training and the employability of early</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">st</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">age researchers</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to enhance the impact of UK researchers by promoting improved career</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">development and management of research staff by research organisations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCUK Statement of Expectations for Equality and Diversity</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">An organization’s success and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">competitiveness depends on its ability to embrace diversity</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and draw on the skills, understanding and experience of its people. The potential rewards of</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">diversity are significant: recruiting staff from the widest possible pool will unlock talent and</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">make a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> major contribution to the impact of research and will benefit the economic and social</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">wellbeing of the UK. RCUK expects that equality and diversity therefore is embedded at all</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">levels and in all aspects of normal research practice.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">RCUK expect those in r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eceipt of Research Council funding to:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">promote and lead cultural change in relation to equalities and diversity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">engage staff at all levels with improving the promotion of equality and diversity</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ensure all members of the research workforce are trained and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> supported to address  disincentives and indirect obstacles to recruitment, retention and progression in research careers</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">provide evidence of ways in which equality and diversity issues are managed at both</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">an institutional and department level</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do num</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">bers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The following paragraphs describe </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a number of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reports of which we are aware that describe issues in education and cultures in the professional SET workforce.  We also summarise the reports which led to the publication of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCUK Statement of Expectations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">for Equality and Diversity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is necessary to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> take into account the early stages in order to begin to understand this. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Existing research suggests that at the age of 10, children tend to be interested in science with little evidence of any gender differences. Yet by the age of 14, this interest has si</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gnificantly declined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This loss of interest is much more marked in girls, to the extent that their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">participation in a number of STEM subjects declines sharply post-16. There is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a strong influence of gender on intended participation and a gender </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gap in perceptions of the subjects which increases as students get older. These findings suggest a need to continue to promote and fund interventions, initiatives and practices that take account of and attempt to reduce gender differences at</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">early stage</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">One suggestion is that careers education should start earlier</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> at around age 11, to help counter the loss of interest in STEM</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Young people and their families have a narrow view of the careers that STEM qualifications can lead to. Many think in terms onl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y of the obvious and traditional routes (scientist, engineer, doctor) and are unaware of the wide range of careers that STEM qualifications make possible. An alternative approach that is used in other countries is to embed information about how STEM is use</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d in the world, and about the people who use it throughout the curriculum</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> literature review </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aiming to synthesise the extant knowledge on the structures, processes and systems that maintain gender inequality in S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ET</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">published </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2008, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bagihole et al. for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the UK Resource Centre for Women in SET</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The report </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">suggest</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisational cultures in SET can discriminate against women despite the existence of equal opportunities policies, particularly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">if cultural norms make it difficult for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women, and men, to take up formal opportunities such a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s family friendly working policies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reports </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the dominant culture in SET is long working hours, task- or project-oriented work and the expectation of total availability, with anything less int</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">erpreted as a lack of commitment to career, profession and organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is important to note that this situation is not peculiar to STEM disciplines. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For example, findings from the International Benchmarking Reviews of the disciplines of Human </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Geography, Sociology, Politics and International Studies and Economics</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> indicate that women’s position in academia in the social sciences mirrors that of their colleagues in STEM disciplines, with women under</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">represented in all four disciplines,  the dispa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rity being greatest at senior levels. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Further, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Bagi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hole et al.’s literature review </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">asserts that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">gender stereotypes that exist in the wider society are also reflected in SET professions; an assumed association between masculinities and technology can mean</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that women are pushed into ‘softer’ areas within SET occupations. These often afford lesser career opportunities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 13.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Although networking has been identified as important for career success, the authors suggest </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">women in SET are often excluded from exis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ting networks that can be both professional and social. Whilst women’s exclusion may not always be explicit, it often exists because many networking opportunities are based on activities traditionally considered to belong to men. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Institute of Physics </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘Project </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Juno</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aims to recognise and reward departments that can demonstrate they have taken action to address the under-representation of women in university physics and to encourage better practice for both women and men</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Juno</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has been an important tool</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for raising awareness among university departments on diversity and inclusion and the IoP intends to evaluate it to ensure that it remains important and appropriate</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Sustainability of the UK Research Workforce Annual Report to the UK Research Base</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Funders Forum 2009</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">RCUK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">presented an </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">analysis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of the participation by females from undergraduate to professor by broad discipline. Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> data, compiled from various HESA publications, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> presented in 11 separate charts in Annex 2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to that report</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In most</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> disciplines the proportion of women has increased at each career stage over time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Particular increases are obs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">erved for example </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lecturers in the Life sciences (up from 25% in 1994 to over 40% in 2007).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Since 2007/08 such detailed analysis has not been possible as the revised pay framework created a lack of comparability between universities grade structures. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is situation should be improved </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ith changes to the HESA data collections from 2012/13</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Recen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t reports have highlighted the reasons that cause the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">poorer progression of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women in academic careers, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the EU report Structu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">al change in research institution</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: Enhancing excellence, gender equality and ef</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">iciency in research and innovation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (European Commi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ssion 2012) </span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> noted </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“Initiatives to promote gender equality in research have been developed in Europe and the US over a number of years. The focus was initially on specific programmes to help women pursue scientific careers. However, those programmes have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">proved to be insufficient to increase the number of women in science, particularly in positions of responsibility, and have not helped to address the structural barriers contributing to the well known leaky pipeline phenomenon. This has led to a shift in f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ocus towards addressing the structural transformation of institutions, using a systemic, comprehensive and sustainable approach.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Notably the Royal Society of Edinburgh Report Tapping All </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ur Talents</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (2012)</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">referring to the wider STEM workforce in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">states:”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We have analysed the factors that cause this loss of talent. Some are the practical hurdles of family responsibility, but</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">many are cultural factors that relate to attitudes in the workplace, the or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ganisation of science and technology with concomitant difficulties in accessing career resources and, inevitably with such a low female representation at senior levels, a lack of role</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">models.”</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The evidence from their report formed part of the evidence base</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for RCUK discussions with the sector to review ways in which Equality and Diversity can best be supported in research. This resulted in the publication of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCUK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Statement of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Expectations for Equality and Diversity</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The statement describes how we </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">expect those in receipt of our funding to promote and lead cultural change in relation to equality and diversity and to provide evidence as to how they are addressing these issues at institutional and departmental level</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> RCUK does </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">not requir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> formal accredi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tation at this time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Research Councils I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nternational reviews (which benchmark UK research activity against the rest of the world) consider the workforce and note issues with female </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">representation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">; e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2010 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">International</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Review of Mathematical Sciences</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">included the finding that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Action about gender diversity is not a sufficiently</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">high priority for the UK mathematical sciences</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research community.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> This reiterates the findings of earlier International reviews</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the 2009 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">International review of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Chemistry</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-f